TY  - JOUR
AU  - Stein, Jeremy C.
T1  - Why are Most Funds Open-End? Competition and the Limits of Arbitrage*
PY  - 2005
Y1  - 2005/02/01
DO  - 10.1162/0033553053327489
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 120
IS  - 1
SP  - 247
EP  - 272
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - The majority of asset-management intermediaries (e.g., mutual funds, hedge funds) are structured on an open-end basis, even though it appears that the open-end form can be a serious impediment to arbitrage. I argue that when funds compete to attract investors' dollars, the equilibrium degree of open-ending in an economy can be excessive from the point of view of these investors. One implication of the analysis is that, even absent short-sales constraints or other frictions, economically large mispricings can coexist with rational, competitive arbitrageurs who earn small excess returns.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1162/0033553053327489
ER  - 



